ce:section.ce:para:
The schematic of our method is described in Fig. 2 a. First, we prepared a sample well array using a 3D printer (Fig. 2b upper) where filter paper disks and sample solutions are placed. Then, we pressed 1/4″-cut filter paper disks into the well as shown in Fig. 2c using a 3D-printed press shown in Fig. 2b bottom. Then, we dropped 10 μL of a GQD colloid in each sample well, fully dried the well in an oven at 50 °C for an hour, and measured the before-brightness (
B 0
) of samples. After that, we placed 45 μL of mercury (II) chloride solution of concentration (
Q
), dried, and measured the after-brightness (
B
). In order to minimize sample variations, we defined each sample's intensity (
I Q
) at the mercury (II) chloride concentration (
Q
) as a normalized value (
