). Fig. 3a images show similar before-brightness regardless of samples and it is desirable consistency. On the other hand, Fig. 3b images show a gradual decrease of brightness with increasing [HgCl2], and the quantitative changes of intensities are plotted in Fig. 3c.

We developed a facile optical method to quantify mercury ion concentration in water using an optical microscope and GQD coated filter paper disks. Our approach is cost-effective, the volume per sample is 6% of conventional fluorescence spectrometer's, and only 45 μL of a liquid sample is necessary for one test. Also, because of this technique's simplicity, it may be easily applied to a portable mercury detection device. Using our method, we obtained the fluorescence intensity vs. [HgCl2] curve, and it can be used to estimate an unknown mercury solution's concentration ranges from 0 to 10 ppm. Detection sensitivity is highly dependent on the concentration of GQD colloids used to coat filter paper disks, and the 10 μL 5 ppm colloids showed the best mercury detection sensitivity among N-GQD colloids in 0–10 ppm mercury (II) chloride solution range. SN-GQD colloid is known to have better sensitivity than N-GQD, and the SN-GQD used in our method also showed better mercury detection sensitivity than N-GQD in 0.4–1.6 ppm of HgCl2 solutions when N- and SN- GQD coated filter papers with similar initial brightness (
B 0
) were compared.
